		</div>
			<div class="col-xs-12 col-sm-12 col-md-9 col-md-offset-3 col-lg-9 col-lg-offset-3">
				<p>Imagine checking out at a clothing store or restaurant and the clerk saying, “we’ll submit this, see what’s covered, and then send you a bill for any balance.” That’s absurd! But, in U.S. healthcare we accept this practice everyday. Both patients and providers have become complacent in their responsibility for the cost of care. Healthcare is the only consumer experience where we “complete” a transaction NOT knowing how much we owe - and for providers, how much we will get paid - and on what timeline.</p> 


				<p>Sy Syms famously said: “An educated consumer is our best customer.” And, he was right! Today, we seldom make a decision  - be it what computer to buy, where to eat, or which route to drive - without first researching VALUE. The internet has allowed for true free market economics. We often choose things based on price, quality, and location. So, if we make every other decision in life as an educated consumer, why should our HEALTH be any different?</p>

				<p>Think about your Amazon shopping experience: Most people first enter their search terms, then check off Prime (if applicable), next  filter for  and last sort by “Price: Low to High”. With this algorithm you will most likely find the greatest VALUE product (highest rated at lowest price) in the top left corner of your screen. This is exactly how it should work - three clicks or less and you have what you need. However, no such experience exists in healthcare.</p> 

				<p>Today, we have three independent groups - Patients, Payors (insurance) and Providers (broadly defined here as individuals, group practices, hospitals, and health systems) -  more or less working in silos for their own benefit, presumably trying to achieve what’s best for you - “good” care. However, incentives are misaligned. Patients want to stay healthy, receive quality care within a good experience, and not break the bank. Payors have one main goal: keep the money. Providers want to see patients lead healthy lives, but more importantly  - on the most basic level - want to get paid (like everyone else)for the hard work they do everyday. Clearly these parties cannot sustainably function in tandem.</p> 

